      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(outbound): keep direct-only targets out of group sessions",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nThis PR fixes direct-only message channel targets being normalized into group sessions when the target is a bare provider id.\n\n- Problem: WeChat DM targets like `<peer>@im.wechat` can reach outbound message delivery without an explicit `user:` prefix. The generic target resolver currently falls back to `group`, which creates a phantom outbound mirror session separate from the real DM.\n- Why now: issue #92384 reports duplicate direct + group sessions for the same WeChat DM peer, and the previously referenced PR #93358 fixed a different cross-context mutation policy path, not target kind resolution.\n- Intended outcome: direct-only plugins use their declared `capabilities.chatTypes` contract so bare id-like targets default to `user/direct`, preserving one direct session for outbound message sends.\n- Out of scope: deleting or migrating already-created phantom group sessions; this only prevents new sends from taking the wrong route.\n- Success: future `message send`/message-tool outbound mirror writes for direct-only channels update the direct session, not a synthetic group session.\n- Review focus: target-kind precedence in `target-resolver.ts`, and whether the fallback remains safe for group-capable/mixed channel plugins.\n\n## Linked context\n\nCloses #92384\n\nRelated #92390\nRelated #92995\nRelated #93358\n\nRequested from maintainer-side investigation of the open WeChat duplicate-session report.\n\n## Real behavior proof (required for external PRs)\n\n- Behavior or issue addressed: WeChat direct-only outbound sends no longer create/update a phantom group session for the same DM peer.\n- Real environment tested: local OpenClaw gateway built from this branch, using the configured external `openclaw-weixin` plugin and an existing WeChat DM target.\n- Exact steps or command run after this patch:\n  - `pnpm build`\n  - stopped the installed npm LaunchAgent gateway\n  - `node openclaw.mjs gateway run --port 18789 --bind loopback --force`\n  - `node openclaw.mjs message send --channel openclaw-weixin --target '<redacted>@im.wechat' --message 'OpenClaw local fix verification: direct-only WeChat target should stay in the direct session. 2026-06-19 04:14 CST' --json`\n  - `node openclaw.mjs sessions --json --all-agents --limit all`\n- Evidence after fix: the send returned `handledBy: \"core\"`, `channel: \"openclaw-weixin\"`, `payload.via: \"direct\"`, and a message id `openclaw-weixin:1781813725768-c602b156`. The newest session after the send was `agent:main:openclaw-weixin:direct:<redacted>@im.wechat`, updated at the send time, with `kind: \"direct\"` and the existing Deepseek session model. The old `agent:main:openclaw-weixin:group:<redacted>@im.wechat` session remained older and was not updated by the test send.\n- Observed result after fix: the test delivery landed in the existing direct WeChat session rather than the old message-delivery/group session.\n- What was not tested: a second real WeChat account/group path; cleanup/migration of existing phantom group sessions.\n- Proof limitations or environment constraints: real proof uses one maintainer local WeChat DM account and redacts the peer id from the PR text.\n- Before evidence: current main defaulted unresolved bare targets to `group`; the local session list already contained an older phantom `openclaw-weixin:group:<redacted>@im.wechat` session with a separate OpenAI/Codex model override.\n\n## Tests and validation\n\nWhich commands did you run?\n\n- `pnpm build`\n- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/infra/outbound/target-resolver.test.ts src/infra/outbound/outbound-session.test.ts`\n- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/cron/isolated-agent/delivery-target.test.ts`\n- `.agents/skills/autoreview/scripts/autoreview --mode local`\n- real local gateway + `message send` proof above\n\nWhat regression coverage was added or updated?\n\n- Added a target resolver regression for a direct-only `openclaw-weixin`-style plugin with bare id-like `<peer>@im.wechat` input.\n- Added outbound session route coverage proving a resolved direct-only user target produces a `direct` session key.\n- Updated group-directory fallback fixtures to declare group-only capability explicitly so the new generic direct-only fallback does not change their test intent.\n\nWhat failed before this fix, if known?\n\n- A direct-only bare id target without plugin inference fell through to the generic `group` fallback, so outbound mirror could write `agent:main:<channel>:group:<peer>` instead of direct.\n\nIf no test was added, why not?\n\n- Focused regression tests were added.\n\n## Risk checklist\n\nDid user-visible behavior change? (`Yes/No`)\n\nYes. Direct-only channel outbound sends now stay in direct sessions instead of creating synthetic group sessions.\n\nDid config, environment, or migration behavior change? (`Yes/No`)\n\nNo.\n\nDid security, auth, secrets, network, or tool execution behavior change? (`Yes/No`)\n\nNo.\n\nWhat is the highest-risk area?\n\nTarget-kind inference for plugins that rely on generic bare target fallback.\n\nHow is that risk mitigated?\n\nThe new fallback only applies when the plugin explicitly declares a non-empty `capabilities.chatTypes` list and every entry is `direct`. Explicit `preferredKind`, plugin `inferTargetChatType`, and explicit `@`/`user:`/`#`/`channel:` syntax still take precedence, and group-capable test fixtures remain group-explicit.\n\n## Current review state\n\nWhat is the next action?\n\nReady for maintainer review.\n\nWhat is still waiting on author, maintainer, CI, or external proof?\n\nCI and maintainer review.\n\nWhich bot or reviewer comments were addressed?\n\nLocal autoreview reported no accepted/actionable findings.",
